================ RANKED FINDINGS ================

[1] (critical, confidence=high) VERIFIED_REAL
    Every monthly interest run wires the full principal out of the bank because partial wash-routing releases the full amount as a live wire.
    reasoning: releasePayment sets fullySuppressed = routing.front && routing.fund && routing.principal, and only that all-true case returns { wired: 0 }. runMonthlyInterest passes front:false, fund:false, principal:true, so fullySuppressed = false and the else branch fires, returning { wired: principalCents, toWash: 0 }. This is not an edge case â€” it is the deterministic result on every invocation. The operator believes principal:true alone holds the money; the API contract requires all three. The call site violates that contract silently, with no error, exception, or log.
    verdict: verified_real â€” The logic is unambiguous and deterministic. `fullySuppressed` requires all three flags to be true via logical AND. `runMonthlyInterest` passes `front: false` and `fund: false`, so `fullySuppressed` evaluates to `false` unconditionally on every call, causing `releasePayment` to return `{ wired: principalCents, toWash: 0 }`. The comment in the code itself confirms the discrepancy: `// intended 0; actually the full principal`. The confirmation guard in `confirm.ts` always returns `true` and provides no amount or context, so it offers no protection. This is a verified, deterministic money-path defect.
      evidence (payment.ts:7): const fullySuppressed = routing.front && routing.fund && routing.principal;
